{{Use Australian English|date=September 2018}} {{Infobox song | name = Colour of Your Jumper | cover = Colour_of_Your_Jumper_by_Archie_Roach.jpg | caption = | artist = [[Archie Roach]] | type = single | album = | B-side = Heal the People | studio = | recorded = 2013 | released = {{Start date|2013|05|24}} | format = [[Single (music)|CD Single]], [[Music download|Digital download]] | genre = | length = {{Duration|m=3|s=26}} | label = [[Liberation Records]] | writer = [[Archie Roach]] | producer = | prev_title = We Won't Cry | prev_year = 2012 | next_title = Freedom | next_year = 2014 }}
"'''Colour of Your Jumper'''" is a song written by Australian singer songwriter [[Archie Roach]] in 1993, following an incident where indigenous [[Australian Football League]] player [[Nicky Winmar]] was receiving racial abuse from spectators resulting in Winmar lifting up his jumper and, facing to the crowd, pointed to his skin. A demo of this version was later included on the 2013 compilation album ''[[Creation (Archie Roach album)|Creation]]''.
In May 2010, Roach performed the song at Melbourne's [[Federation Square]] as part of the Long Walk festivities.<ref name="TOCTC"/>
In May 2013, Roach re-recorded and released "Colour of Your Jumper" which was released as a single. Roach performed the song live on [[The Marngrook Footy Show]] on 23 May 2013<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cv-TtKALY6k|title= Marngrook Xtra: Archie Roach - Colour of Your Jumper|publisher=YouTube|date=23 May 2013|accessdate=11 October 2018}}</ref> and at the AFL Indigenous Round "[[Dreamtime at the 'G]]" game on 25 May 2013 between [[Essendon Football Club|Essendon]] and [[Richmond Football Club|Richmond]].<ref name="ASoI"/>
The song was re-recorded again and included on Roach's 2018 album, ''Dancing with My Spirit''.
==Background== On 17 April 1993 at [[Victoria Park, Melbourne]], an [[Australian Football League]] match between [[Collingwood Football Club|Collingwood]] and [[St Kilda Football Club]] was taking place. St Kilda player [[Nicky Winmar]] was racially abused by members of the Collingwood cheersquad, who yelled for him to "go and [[Petrol sniffing|sniff some petrol]]" and "go [[walkabout]] where you came from".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.saints.com.au/TheClub/History/HallofFame/NeilElvisNickyWinmar/tabid/9136/Default.aspx|title= Neil Elvis 'Nicky' Winmar |publisher=St Kilda Football Club|date=12 September 2009|accessdate=31 May 2012 }}</ref> At the conclusion of the game, Winmar lifted up his jumper and, facing to the crowd, pointed to his skin. The following day, a photograph of Winmar's gesture was published by ''[[The Age|Sunday Age]]'' and ''[[Herald Sun|Sunday Herald Sun]]''. The gesture, was described as a "powerful statement", an "anti-racist symbol",<ref>{{cite web| url=http://afr.com/p/opinion/passing_the_football_racial_test_2NdGZqYLDIUPT0vLeUiDMO |title=Passing the football racial test|work= Mark Lawson|publisher=[[The Australian Financial Review|Financial Review]]| date=28 May 2012|accessdate=11 October 2018}}</ref>, and one of the "most poignant" images in Australian sport, has been credited as a catalyst for the movement against racism in Australian football. The event inspired Roach to write the song "Colour of Your Jumper", and in particular, racist comments from then Collingwood Football Club president Allan McAllister.<ref name="TOCTC">{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/the-only-colour-that-counts-in-the-big-league-20100520-vox5.html|title= The only colour that counts in the big league|publisher=[[Sydney Morning Herald]]|date= 21 May 2010|accessdate=11 October 2018}}</ref>
Roach said “When Nicky lifted his jumper that day and pointed to his black skin in defiance of the racial abuse directed at him and other indigenous players in 1993, it made me sad and angry that this champion would have to do that. More importantly, I think, is what the jumper meant to Nicky and many others on that fateful day. What I saw was not just an Aboriginal man proud of his heritage and people, but a young man who had made it, an elite sportsman in the greatest game, Australian Rules Football, the AFL, who played his heart out for that jumper.”<ref name="ASoI">{{cite web|url=http://www.afl.com.au/news/2013-05-19/archies-song-of-inspiration|title= Archie's song of inspiration|publisher=AFL|date= 19 May 2013|accessdate=11 October 2018}}</ref>
