{{infobox country at games | NOC = ECU | NOCname = [[Ecuadorian National Olympic Committee]] | games = Olympics | year = | flagcaption = | oldcode = | website = {{url|www.coe.org.ec }}&nbsp;{{es icon}} | location = | competitors = | sports = | flagbearer = | rank = | gold = 1 | silver = 1 | bronze = 0 | officials = | appearances = | app_begin_year = | app_end_year = | summerappearances = {{Team appearances list|team=Ecuador|competition=Summer Olympics|begin_year=|end_year= }} | winterappearances = {{Team appearances list|team=Ecuador|competition=Winter Olympics|begin_year=2018|end_year= }} | seealso = }} '''[[Ecuador]]''' has competed in 12 [[Summer Olympic Games]]. They debuted in the [[Winter Olympic Games]] in 2018. The nation from [[South America]] won its first medal when [[Jefferson Pérez]] won the gold medal in the men's 20&nbsp;km walk at the 1996 Olympic Games. The [[Ecuadorian National Olympic Committee]] was created in 1948 and recognized by the [[IOC]] in 1959.
The country made its Winter Olympics debut in 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.coe.org.ec/index.php/noticias/183-noticias-coe/2665-klaus-jungbluth-es-el-primer-ecuatoriano-que-participara-en-juegos-olimpicos-de-invierno|title=Klaus Jungbluth es el primer ecuatoriano que participará en Juegos Olímpicos de Invierno|trans-title=Klaus Jungbluth is the first Ecuadorian to participate in the Olympic Winter Games|language=Spanish|last=Santos|first=Manuela|date=16 October 2017|website=www.coe.org.ec/|publisher=[[Ecuadorian National Olympic Committee]]|access-date=25 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.eluniverso.com/deportes/2017/12/08/nota/6516319/jungbluth-tricolor-pyeongchang-2018|title=Klaus Jungbluth, un tricolor en Pyeongchang 2018|trans-title=Klaus Jungbluth, a tricolor in Pyeongchang 2018|language=Spanish|date=8 December 2017|location=[[Guayaquil]]|work=[[El Universo]]|access-date=25 December 2017}}</ref>
